26 September 2019

Background

  • Over 750,000 16-24 year olds are Not in Education, Employment, or Training (NEET) in the UK (ONS 2019).

  • Youth worklessness - and youth unemployment, specifically - is associated with worse mental health in later life.

  • Long-term associations are typically termed “scarring effects” (Clark, Georgellis, and Sanfey 2001).

Research Questions

  • Here, we see whether the association with mental health at age 25 is moderated by:
    • Gender
    • Adolescent Neighbourhood Deprivation
    • Family Socio-Economic Class
    • Locus of Control (LOC)
    • Preferences for Employment

Locus of Control

  • “[A] generalized attitude, belief, or expectancy regarding the nature of the causal relationship between ones own behavior and its consequences” (Rotter 1966, 2).

  • Internal LOC: outcomes consequences of own own actions.

  • External LOC: outcomes determined by others, luck, etc.

Hypotheses



  1. 6+ months NEET between ages 18-20 will be associated with worse mental health at age 25.

  2. The association will be stronger amongst:
    • Males
    • Those with more external locus of control
    • Those from lower socio-economic class backgrounds
    • Those from more deprived neighbourhoods
    • Those with who prefer any job to unemployment

Dataset

  • Next Steps (formerly, the Longitudinal Study of Young People in England).

  • Participants recruited from English secondary schools at age 13/14 in 2003/04 (n=15,770).
    • Sample boost of 352 BAME participants recruited at age 16/17.
  • Outcome: GHQ-12 Likert Score @ Age 25 (2015/16)
    • Higher values indicate worse health
  • Exposure: 6+ months NEET between October 2008-May 2010
    • Age 18-20, post A-Levels.

Measurement Periods

Moderators

  • Gender

  • Index of Multiple Deprivation (IMD) @ Age 14/15
    • LSOA of residence (400-1,200 households).
    • Higher values indicate greater deprivation

  • Family Five Class NS-SEC @ Age 13/14

  • Internal Locus of Control @ Age 14/15
    • Sum of three items.
    • Higher values indicate greater internal LOC
  • Employment Preference @ Age 13/14
    • (Dis)agreement with statement “Having any kind of job is better than being unemployed”

Methods

\[GHQ_{Age 25, i} = \beta_{0} + \beta_{1} \cdot NEET_{i} + \beta_{2} \cdot NEET_{i} \cdot M_{i,j} + \beta_{J} \cdot M + \beta_{K} \cdot X_{i}\]

  • OLS regression with interaction term for each moderator in turn.

  • Survey weights used to account for attrition.

  • Missing data imputed using Tilling et al. (2016) method for interactions.
    • m = 50, burn in = 25.
    • Survey weights added as linear term.

  • n = 7,363

Control Variables (\(X_{i}\))

  • Health:
    • GHQ-12 Likert @ Age 14/15 & Age 16/17
    • Self-Rated Health @ Age 14/15
    • Disability @ Age 14/15
  • Risk:
    • School Attitude @ Age 14/15 (12 item measure)
    • Risk Behaviours @ Age 14/15 (8 item measure)
  • Demographics:
    • Ethnicity
    • English Speaking Household @ Age 13/14
    • Household Type @ Age 13/14
    • Education Level @ Age 25

Discussion

  • 6+ month NEET episode associated with poorer mental health 5-7 years later.

  • Results consistent with (most) hypotheses, but estimates imprecise

  • Research should move from overall associations to moderation and mediation.

  • Findings may be specific to cohort entering adulthood during recession.

Limitations

  • NEET concept covers diverse circumstances (Furlong 2006).

  • Observational design

  • Measurement error

  • Collider bias

  • High attrition (52.3%)
